# PHASE 6 — ZERO-TRUST SECRETS MANAGEMENT WITH VAULT

[## [SECTION: The Problem Vault Solves]]


1
02:32:06,000 --> 02:32:12,000
Now let's move to Phase 6. Zero-trust secrets management with HashiCorp Vault.
This is how production systems handle secrets safely.

2
02:32:12,000 --> 02:32:18,000
In Phases 1 through 5, secrets live in .env and are injected as environment variables.
This has three problems at production scale.

3
02:32:18,000 --> 02:32:24,000
First, static credentials. If POSTGRES_PASSWORD leaks, it works forever.
Until someone manually rotates it, the attacker has access.

4
02:32:24,000 --> 02:32:30,000
Second, shared credentials. Every pod uses the same password.
If the ingestion service is compromised, the attacker has database access identical to the API service.

5
02:32:30,000 --> 02:32:36,000
Third, environment variable exposure. Any process in the container can read os.environ.
Secrets in files with restricted permissions are harder to exfiltrate.

6
02:32:36,000 --> 02:32:42,000
Vault solves all three.
Dynamic credentials rotate automatically every hour.

7
02:32:42,000 --> 02:32:48,000
Per-role credentials. API, agent, and ingestion each get different database users.
With different privileges for each workload.

8
02:32:48,000 --> 02:32:54,000
File-based injection. Vault Agent writes secrets to files that only the application process can read.

9
02:32:54,000 --> 02:33:00,000
Imagine you have a big, yummy box of cookies. Those are your secrets.

10
02:33:00,000 --> 02:33:06,000
Right now, you have one giant jar of cookies that stays on the counter all day.
That's your .env file with all your secrets in one place.

11
02:33:06,000 --> 02:33:12,000
If a naughty monkey comes into your kitchen, he can just walk up.
Grab the whole jar, and eat all the cookies at once.

12
02:33:12,000 --> 02:33:18,000
That's the problem with static credentials in environment variables.
One leak exposes everything, and the credentials work forever.

13
02:33:18,000 --> 02:33:24,000
Vault is like having a special cookie guard.
It completely changes how secrets are managed.

14
02:33:24,000 --> 02:33:30,000
First, the guard has a magic key. Only you get to wear the magic key.
That's your Kubernetes service account.

15
02:33:30,000 --> 02:33:36,000
Second, no more jar. Instead of leaving the big jar out,
the guard keeps it locked away in a tall, tall cupboard.

16
02:33:36,000 --> 02:33:42,000
Third, one tiny cookie at a time. When you are hungry, you show the guard your magic key.

17
02:33:42,000 --> 02:33:48,000
He nods and says okay. He goes to the cupboard.
Takes out just one tiny cookie, and puts it on your plate.

18
02:33:48,000 --> 02:33:54,000
That's the Vault Agent. It puts the secret in a file.
Not in an environment variable where any process can read it.

19
02:33:54,000 --> 02:34:00,000
Fourth, the cookie disappears. After a little while, that cookie vanishes.
If you want another, you show the magic key again.

20
02:34:00,000 --> 02:34:06,000
That's dynamic credentials. They rotate automatically.
If a secret leaks, it only works for a short time.

21
02:34:06,000 --> 02:34:12,000
So, if that naughty monkey comes into the kitchen,
he can't find any cookies. The jar is locked away.

22
02:34:12,000 --> 02:34:18,000
Even if he does find one tiny cookie on your plate,
it disappears so fast he can't steal the whole jar.

23
02:34:18,000 --> 02:34:24,000
That's the zero-trust model. No standing privileges.
Every request re-authenticates. Every secret has a short lifespan.


