[## [SECTION: Step 1 — Understand the Vault Architecture]]


34
02:35:24,000 --> 02:35:30,000
Before writing any code, understand how the components connect.

35
02:35:30,000 --> 02:35:36,000
At the center is HashiCorp Vault.
It runs three engines. The database engine for PostgreSQL credentials.

36
02:35:36,000 --> 02:35:42,000
The PKI engine for short-lived TLS certificates.
And the Kubernetes auth method for pod authentication.

37
02:35:42,000 --> 02:35:48,000
Next is the Vault Agent sidecar.
It runs in the same pod as your application container.

38
02:35:48,000 --> 02:35:54,000
The sidecar reads the Kubernetes service account JWT token.
It authenticates to Vault using that token.

39
02:35:54,000 --> 02:36:00,000
Then it writes secrets to a shared volume.
The volume is mounted at slash vault slash secrets.

40
02:36:00,000 --> 02:36:06,000
Your application container reads from that file.
It never talks to Vault directly in normal operation.

41
02:36:06,000 --> 02:36:12,000
Here is the key insight.
The application never talks to Vault directly in normal operation.

42
02:36:12,000 --> 02:36:18,000
Vault Agent handles all authentication and secret renewal.
The app just reads files from disk.

43
02:36:18,000 --> 02:36:24,000
This is much simpler and more secure.
No Vault client code in your application at all.


[## [SECTION: Step 2 — Install Vault on Kubernetes (Component #52)]]


44
02:36:24,000 --> 02:36:30,000
Now let's install Vault on Kubernetes.
We'll use the official HashiCorp Helm chart.

45
02:36:30,000 --> 02:36:36,000
First, add the HashiCorp Helm repository and update it.
Then install Vault in dev mode.

46
02:36:36,000 --> 02:36:42,000
Dev mode starts a single Vault pod with no high availability.
It uses in-memory storage, which loses all data on restart.

47
02:36:42,000 --> 02:36:48,000
This is only for learning the workflow.
Production requires HA mode with Raft storage and auto-unseal.

48
02:36:48,000 --> 02:36:54,000
Wait for Vault to be ready with kubectl wait.
Then verify the status with vault status.

49
02:36:54,000 --> 02:37:00,000
Expected output shows Seal Type shamir, Initialized true, Sealed false.
If it says Sealed true, something went wrong.


[## [SECTION: Step 3 — Vault Bootstrap Script (Components #53–63)]]


50
02:37:00,000 --> 02:37:06,000
Now let's create the Vault bootstrap script.
This script automates the entire Vault configuration.

51
02:37:06,000 --> 02:37:12,000
It's idempotent, meaning you can run it multiple times safely.
Each command checks for existing configuration before creating it.

52
02:37:12,000 --> 02:37:18,000
Create infrastructure slash vault slash vault-bootstrap.sh.
Make it executable with chmod plus x.

53
02:37:18,000 --> 02:37:24,000
The script does ten things in order.
Let me walk through each component.

54
02:37:24,000 --> 02:37:30,000
First, it enables the database secrets engine.
This tells Vault to manage PostgreSQL credentials.

55
02:37:30,000 --> 02:37:36,000
Second, it configures the PostgreSQL connection.
Vault needs admin credentials to create and revoke database users.

56
02:37:36,000 --> 02:37:42,000
Third, it creates three database roles.
One for each service. API, agent, and ingestion.

57
02:37:42,000 --> 02:37:48,000
The API role gets read-only access to filings and financial chunks.
Plus insert on analysis_history for the audit trail.

58
02:37:48,000 --> 02:37:54,000
The agent role gets read access to filings and financial chunks.
And read-write on analysis_history.

59
02:37:54,000 --> 02:38:00,000
The ingestion role gets select, insert, and update on filings and financial chunks.
And usage on all sequences in the public schema.

60
02:38:00,000 --> 02:38:06,000
Fourth, it enables the PKI secrets engine.
PKI stands for Public Key Infrastructure. It handles certificates.

61
02:38:06,000 --> 02:38:12,000
Fifth, it generates a root certificate for the internal certificate authority.
This root CA signs all service certificates.

62
02:38:12,000 --> 02:38:18,000
Sixth, it creates a PKI role for financial rag.
This role defines which domains are allowed and the certificate lifespan.

63
02:38:18,000 --> 02:38:24,000
Seventh, it enables the Kubernetes auth method.
This allows pods to authenticate using their service account.

64
02:38:24,000 --> 02:38:30,000
Eighth, it configures Kubernetes auth.
It reads the cluster's API server address and CA certificate.

65
02:38:30,000 --> 02:38:36,000
Ninth, it writes three Vault policies.
One for each service with least-privilege access.

66
02:38:36,000 --> 02:38:42,000
The API policy can read LLM keys, Redis password, and database credentials.
It can also issue PKI certificates.

67
02:38:42,000 --> 02:38:48,000
The agent policy can read LLM keys, Redis password, and database credentials.
But no PKI access.

68
02:38:48,000 --> 02:38:54,000
The ingestion policy can read Edgar credentials, Redis password, and database credentials.
No LLM or PKI access.

69
02:38:54,000 --> 02:39:00,000
Tenth, it creates Kubernetes auth roles.
Each role binds a service account to a Vault policy.

70
02:39:00,000 --> 02:39:06,000
The API service account gets the API policy.
The agent service account gets the agent policy.

71
02:39:06,000 --> 02:39:12,000
The ingestion service account gets the ingestion policy.
Each with different TTLs.

72
02:39:12,000 --> 02:39:18,000
Finally, the script seeds static secrets.
These are the secrets that aren't dynamically generated.

73
02:39:18,000 --> 02:39:24,000
LLM API keys, Redis password, Edgar user agent, and config values.
You must replace the placeholders before production use.

74
02:39:24,000 --> 02:39:30,000
To run the script, set your PostgreSQL admin password.
Then execute vault-bootstrap.sh from within the Vault pod.

75
02:39:30,000 --> 02:39:36,000
kubectl exec dash it vault dash 0 dash n vault
Then bash dash c, then the script path.

76
02:39:36,000 --> 02:39:42,000
After it completes, verify with vault read database slash creds slash api dash role.
You should see dynamic credentials generated.

77
02:39:42,000 --> 02:39:48,000
Let me summarize the bootstrap workflow.

78
02:39:48,000 --> 02:39:54,000
Enable database engine. Configure PostgreSQL. Create database roles.
Enable PKI. Generate root CA. Create PKI role.

79
02:39:54,000 --> 02:40:00,000
Enable Kubernetes auth. Configure Kubernetes. Create policies.
Create auth roles. Seed static secrets.

80
02:40:00,000 --> 02:40:06,000
Our Vault bootstrap is complete.
Now Vault is ready to provide dynamic credentials to our services.


[## [SECTION: Step 4 — Vault Policies (Component #62)]]


81
02:40:06,000 --> 02:40:12,000
Now let's create the Vault policies as separate files.
For audit and GitOps tracking, we store them in infrastructure/vault/policies.

82
02:40:12,000 --> 02:40:18,000
First, api-policy.hcl.
This is the least-privilege policy for the API service.

83
02:40:18,000 --> 02:40:24,000
It can read LLM secrets, Redis secrets, and config secrets.
It can read dynamic database credentials for the API role.

84
02:40:24,000 --> 02:40:30,000
And it can create and update PKI certificates.
For mTLS between services.

85
02:40:30,000 --> 02:40:36,000
Second, agent-policy.hcl.
The agent service needs LLM access and Redis.

86
02:40:36,000 --> 02:40:42,000
It can read database credentials for the agent role.
But it cannot issue PKI certificates.

87
02:40:42,000 --> 02:40:48,000
Third, ingestion-policy.hcl.
The ingestion service only needs EDGAR config and Redis.

88
02:40:48,000 --> 02:40:54,000
Notice what's missing. No LLM API key access.
Ingestion does not call the LLM.

89
02:40:54,000 --> 02:41:00,000
Why three separate policies?
This is the principle of least privilege per workload.

90
02:41:00,000 --> 02:41:06,000
If the ingestion service is compromised, the attacker cannot call the LLM.
The API service does not need EDGAR credentials.

91
02:41:06,000 --> 02:41:12,000
Compartmentalisation limits the blast radius.
Each service gets exactly what it needs, nothing more.


[## [SECTION: Step 5 — Kubernetes Service Accounts (Component #64)]]


92
02:41:12,000 --> 02:41:18,000
Now let's create the Kubernetes service accounts.
One per workload.

93
02:41:18,000 --> 02:41:24,000
Create infrastructure slash k8s slash service-accounts.yaml.
We define three service accounts.

94
02:41:24,000 --> 02:41:30,000
financial-rag-agent-api for the API service.
financial-rag-agent-agent for the agent service.

95
02:41:30,000 --> 02:41:36,000
And financial-rag-agent-ingestion for the ingestion service.
Each in the financial-rag namespace.

96
02:41:36,000 --> 02:41:42,000
Apply them with kubectl create namespace if it doesn't exist.
Then kubectl apply dash f.

97
02:41:42,000 --> 02:41:48,000
These service accounts will be used by the Vault Agent sidecar.
Each maps to a different Vault policy.


[## [SECTION: Step 6 — Vault Agent Sidecar Config (Component #65)]]


98
02:41:48,000 --> 02:41:54,000
Now let's configure the Vault Agent sidecar.
This runs as a second container in each pod.

99
02:41:54,000 --> 02:42:00,000
Create infrastructure slash vault slash vault-agent-config.hcl.
Let me explain what this configuration does.

100
02:42:00,000 --> 02:42:06,000
First, the vault block sets the Vault address.
http colon slash slash vault dot vault dot svc dot cluster dot local colon 8200.

101
02:42:06,000 --> 02:42:12,000
This is the Kubernetes internal DNS name for Vault.
All pods in the cluster can reach it.

102
02:42:12,000 --> 02:42:18,000
Next, auto_auth tells Vault how to authenticate.
We use the Kubernetes auth method.

103
02:42:18,000 --> 02:42:24,000
The sidecar reads the pod's service account JWT.
It presents this token to Vault.

104
02:42:24,000 --> 02:42:30,000
The role must match the service account.
We set it via an environment variable on the sidecar.

105
02:42:30,000 --> 02:42:36,000
Now the template blocks.
These render secrets into files.

106
02:42:36,000 --> 02:42:42,000
The first template renders database credentials.
It calls the secret command to get dynamic credentials.

107
02:42:42,000 --> 02:42:48,000
The output goes to slash vault slash secrets slash database.env.
The format is environment variables.

108
02:42:48,000 --> 02:42:54,000
When credentials rotate, the command runs kill dash HUP.
This sends a signal to the application to reload.

109
02:42:54,000 --> 02:43:00,000
The annotation approach uses Vault's mutating admission webhook.
It automatically injects the sidecar without changing the deployment spec.

110
02:43:00,000 --> 02:43:06,000
Here are the annotations for a deployment.
vault.hashicorp.com slash agent-inject set to true.

111
02:43:06,000 --> 02:43:12,000
vault.hashicorp.com slash role specifies which Vault role to use.
And agent-inject-secret plus agent-inject-template define each secret.

112
02:43:12,000 --> 02:43:18,000
This is the recommended production pattern.
No manual sidecar configuration needed.


[## [SECTION: Step 7 — Deploy and Test the Sidecar (Component #66)]]


113
02:43:18,000 --> 02:43:24,000
Now let's test the Vault Agent sidecar.
We'll deploy a test pod with the API service account.

114
02:43:24,000 --> 02:43:30,000
This pod has the Vault Agent annotations.
It will automatically inject the sidecar and fetch secrets.

115
02:43:30,000 --> 02:43:36,000
We create a simple pod with the busybox image.
It just sleeps for 3600 seconds so we can inspect it.

116
02:43:36,000 --> 02:43:42,000
The annotations tell Vault to inject the sidecar.
And to fetch the database secret from the API role.

117
02:43:42,000 --> 02:43:48,000
Wait for the pod to be ready with kubectl wait.
Then inspect the injected secret file.

118
02:43:48,000 --> 02:43:54,000
The expected output shows POSTGRES_USER and POSTGRES_PASSWORD.
Notice the username starts with v dash k8s dash api dash role.

119
02:43:54,000 --> 02:44:00,000
This is a dynamically generated credential.
Unique per pod, rotated automatically after one hour.

120
02:44:00,000 --> 02:44:06,000
If you run the test multiple times, you'll get different usernames.
Each time, Vault creates a new database user.

121
02:44:06,000 --> 02:44:12,000
Clean up the test pod when done.
kubectl delete pod vault-test in the financial-rag namespace.


[## [SECTION: Step 8 — Python Vault Client (Component #67)]]


122
02:44:12,000 --> 02:44:18,000
Now let's build the Python Vault client.
We'll put it in src/financial_rag/security/vault.py

123
02:44:18,000 --> 02:44:24,000
This client handles reading secrets from Vault.
But with an important design decision.

124
02:44:24,000 --> 02:44:30,000
The client has a three-tier priority order.
First, try file-based injection from the Vault Agent sidecar.

125
02:44:30,000 --> 02:44:36,000
This is the production path. Secrets are written to slash vault slash secrets.
As dot env files that the app can read.

126
02:44:36,000 --> 02:44:42,000
Second, if no file exists, try direct Vault API using hvac.
This is for development when running Vault locally.

127
02:44:42,000 --> 02:44:48,000
Third, fall back to environment variables.
This is for local development without Vault at all.

128
02:44:48,000 --> 02:44:54,000
The VaultSecretReader class has a read method.
It takes a secret name like database or llm.

129
02:44:54,000 --> 02:45:00,000
In production, it looks for slash vault slash secrets slash database.env.
It parses the KEY=VALUE pairs and returns them as a dictionary.

130
02:45:00,000 --> 02:45:06,000
The _parse_env_file method handles the file parsing.
It skips comments and blank lines.

131
02:45:06,000 --> 02:45:12,000
If the file doesn't exist, we try direct Vault API.
We need VAULT_ADDR and VAULT_TOKEN environment variables.

132
02:45:12,000 --> 02:45:18,000
For static secrets like LLM keys, we use the KV v2 engine.
For dynamic database credentials, we use the database engine.

133
02:45:18,000 --> 02:45:24,000
The read_database_credentials method is a convenience wrapper.
It specifically reads the database secret.

134
02:45:24,000 --> 02:45:30,000
We use a module-level singleton for the Vault reader.
get_vault_reader returns the same instance every time.

135
02:45:30,000 --> 02:45:36,000
Update the security package __init__.py.
Export VaultSecretReader and get_vault_reader.

136
02:45:36,000 --> 02:45:42,000
Install the hvac library first.
pip install hvac.

137
02:45:42,000 --> 02:45:48,000
Let me summarize the Vault client design.

138
02:45:48,000 --> 02:45:54,000
The key insight is that the application never talks to Vault directly.
In production, the sidecar handles everything.

139
02:45:54,000 --> 02:46:00,000
The app just reads files from slash vault slash secrets.
This is much simpler and more secure.

140
02:46:00,000 --> 02:46:06,000
The direct Vault API path is only for development.
And for testing when you don't have the sidecar.

141
02:46:06,000 --> 02:46:12,000
In production, VAULT_ADDR and VAULT_TOKEN are not set.
So the client only uses the file path.

142
02:46:12,000 --> 02:46:18,000
Our Python Vault client is complete.
Now our application can read secrets from Vault seamlessly.


[## [SECTION: Step 9 — OPA Rego Policy for Vault (Component #74 preview)]]


143
02:46:18,000 --> 02:46:24,000
Now let's look at OPA Rego policy validation for Vault.
This ensures our Vault policies are secure before they are applied.

144
02:46:24,000 --> 02:46:30,000
OPA stands for Open Policy Agent. It's a general-purpose policy engine.
We use it to validate Vault policy files.

145
02:46:30,000 --> 02:46:36,000
Install conftest first. pip install conftest.
This tool evaluates policies against your policy files.

146
02:46:36,000 --> 02:46:42,000
We create a test input with a bad policy.
It grants write on a wildcard secret path.

147
02:46:42,000 --> 02:46:48,000
And delete capability on that same path.
These are dangerous permissions.

148
02:46:48,000 --> 02:46:54,000
We run conftest test against this input.
Using the vault_policy.rego file from our repo.

149
02:46:54,000 --> 02:47:00,000
The output shows two failures.
One for wildcard write, one for delete capability.

150
02:47:00,000 --> 02:47:06,000
The Rego policy enforces three rules.
No wildcard write on secret paths.

151
02:47:06,000 --> 02:47:12,000
No delete capability on secret paths.
Application roles should never delete secrets.

152
02:47:12,000 --> 02:47:18,000
No sudo capability except for admin policies.
And no sys slash access from non-admin workloads.


[## [SECTION: Step 10 — Production Vault HA (Component #68)]]


153
02:47:18,000 --> 02:47:24,000
Now let's deploy Vault in production HA mode.
We upgrade the Helm chart with different settings.

154
02:47:24,000 --> 02:47:30,000
Dev mode is disabled. HA mode is enabled.
We use three replicas for high availability.

155
02:47:30,000 --> 02:47:36,000
Raft storage is enabled. This is Vault's built-in consensus algorithm.
It replaces Consul storage.

156
02:47:36,000 --> 02:47:42,000
Data storage is enabled with 10 gigabytes per replica.
And the web UI is enabled for management.

157
02:47:42,000 --> 02:47:48,000
In production, Vault must be unsealed after every restart.
Manual unsealing is operationally painful.

158
02:47:48,000 --> 02:47:54,000
You need 3 out of 5 key shares to unseal.
That means someone must type three different keys.

159
02:47:54,000 --> 02:48:00,000
AWS KMS auto-unseal solves this.
Vault unseals itself using a KMS key you control.

160
02:48:00,000 --> 02:48:06,000
The seal block goes in your Helm values as extraConfig.
Region, and the KMS key ARN.

161
02:48:06,000 --> 02:48:12,000
When Vault starts, it calls the KMS service.
The KMS key decrypts Vault's master key automatically.

162
02:48:12,000 --> 02:48:18,000
No human intervention needed. Vault just works after restarts.

163
02:48:18,000 --> 02:48:24,000
Now let's set up Raft snapshot backups.
A manual snapshot command saves the Vault state.

164
02:48:24,000 --> 02:48:30,000
Use this before upgrades or major changes.

165
02:48:30,000 --> 02:48:36,000
For automated backups, we use a Kubernetes CronJob.
It runs daily at 2 AM.

166
02:48:36,000 --> 02:48:42,000
The job calls vault operator raft snapshot save.
Then uploads the snapshot to S3.


[## [SECTION: Step 11 — Phase 6 Verification]]

167
02:48:42,000 --> 02:48:48,000
Now let's verify everything works.
First, read dynamic database credentials from Vault.

168
02:48:48,000 --> 02:48:54,000
vault read database slash creds slash api-role.
You get a lease ID, lease duration of one hour, username, and password.

169
02:48:54,000 --> 02:49:00,000
The username starts with v dash k8s dash api dash role.
The password is a secure random string.

170
02:49:00,000 --> 02:49:06,000
Next, verify the credential actually works in PostgreSQL.
Use PGPASSWORD with the password, then run a SELECT query.

171
02:49:06,000 --> 02:49:12,000
If the query succeeds, your dynamic credentials are working.

172
02:49:12,000 --> 02:49:18,000
Finally, verify the policy denies what it should.
Create a token with the api-policy.

